04137nam a22006375i 9780271056586DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710565867 a10.1515/97802710565862doi  a(DE-B1597)584174  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBJ1395b.O26 2008eb 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a170/.422221 aO'Connor, Peg, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMorality and Our Complicated Form of Life :bFeminist Wittgensteinian Metaethics /cPeg O'Connor. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tacknowledgments -- tprolegomenon to any future feminist metaethics -- tlist of abbreviations -- t1. Feminist Wittgensteinian Metaethics? Revising the Big Book -- t2. Does the Fabric of the World Include Moral Properties? Realist/Antirealist Debates -- t3. Neither a Realist nor an Antirealist Be -- t4. Felted Contextualism: Heterogeneous Stability -- t5. Normativity and Grammar -- t6. Philosophical Rags and Mice: Changing the Subject in Moral Epistemology -- t7. Stability and Objectivity: The Felted World -- tbibliography -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoral philosophy, like much of philosophy generally, has been bedeviled by an obsession with seeking secure epistemological foundations and with dichotomies between mind and body, fact and value, subjectivity and objectivity, nature and normativity. These are still alive today in the realism-versus-antirealism debates in ethics. Peg O'Connor draws inspiration from the later Wittgenstein's philosophy to sidestep these pitfalls and develop a new approach to the grounding of ethics (i.e., metaethics) that looks to the interconnected nature of social practices, most especially those that Wittgenstein called "language games." These language games provide structure and stability to our moral lives while they permit the flexibility to accommodate change in moral understandings and attitudes. To this end, O'Connor deploys new metaphors from architecture and knitting to describe her approach as "felted stabilism," which locates morality in a large set of overlapping and crisscrossing language games such as engaging in moral inquiry, seeking justifications for our beliefs and actions, formulating reasons for actions, making judgments, disagreeing with other people or dissenting from dominant norms, manifesting moral understandings, and taking and assigning responsibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEthics. 0aFeminist ethics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056586423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056586.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK